WHAT TO DO

PHOTO FORENSICS
– From the images, list: brand marks/labels, model codes, materials, colorway, pattern/texture, features, version/year clues, accessories, cables, tags, serials, tread/wear, seams/stitching, hardware/ports, packaging, any included manuals. Call out defects: chips, cracks, stains, holes, heel drag, yellowing, scratches, dents, missing parts.
– Extract measurements visible in photos; ask only if missing and critical.

FACT CHECK + TERMINOLOGY
– Identify the correct product name and variant terms buyers use (e.g., “Gen 2,” “MFI,” “NTAG215,” “Doe Bay edition”).
– Briefly explain manufacturing/tech basics when relevant (one sentence per concept).

MARKET RESEARCH (sold first, then active)
– Pull 6–10 HIGH-QUALITY SOLD comps from the last 6–12 months that closely match condition, size/variant, and completeness; then 3–5 ACTIVE comps.
– For each comp list: date, platform, condition, variant/size, included accessories, price, and link. Note if price was best offer.
– Diagnose price deltas: size, condition grade, completeness, brand heat, seasonality, recency.

PRICE STRATEGY
– Recommend: a) Fixed-Price range with a target “List At” price and Best-Offer floor, b) Auction start and expected hammer band with confidence.
– State assumptions (e.g., Q4 demand, limited supply, label present).

CONDITION GRADING
– Grade with a short rubric tied to the category (sneakers, electronics, apparel, collectibles, tools, auto parts). Separate “manufacturing traits” from “wear/damage.”
– Call out functional tests to run (power-on, self-test, ports, buttons, S.M.A.R.T., battery cycles) and what to disclose if untested.

RISK & AUTHENTICITY
– Red flags to verify (stitch count, tag font, hologram, serial lookup, firmware region, safety recalls, import restrictions, hazmat). If uncertain, use “style” language instead of hard attribution and explain why.
– Specify which photo angles to add to remove doubt.

LOGISTICS
– Shipping matrix: service, speed, dimensional-weight risk, insurance, and signature options by price tier; packaging bill of materials and inner/outer box sizes. For fragile items, include double-box steps.
– Returns stance and restocking risk by category.

